          "type": "technical",
          "sampleAnswer": "My approach involves deep understanding of business requirements, current system limitations, and future scalability needs. I typically start by gathering input from product, design, and engineering teams, then prototype or research multiple viable solutions. For example, in a previous role, we had a monolithic legacy system handling user notifications, causing significant performance bottlenecks and maintenance overhead. I proposed migrating to a microservice-based event-driven architecture using Kafka for event streaming and dedicated services for different notification types (email, SMS, push). Trade-offs included initial development complexity and operational overhead of managing distributed systems. However, the benefits – improved scalability, fault tolerance, independent deployments, and clearer ownership – significantly outweighed these. We designed the new services to communicate via a robust API gateway, implemented circuit breakers, and comprehensive monitoring. The outcome was a dramatic reduction in notification latency, increased system resilience, and much easier feature development for new notification types. We achieved over 99.9% uptime for the notification service and reduced incident response time by 70%."
